    <!-- Section 8: Multi-environment -->
    <h2><span class="keyword">Multi-environment</span> - branches vs folders</h2>

    <p>How do you manage dev, staging and production in a GitOps repo? Two approaches exist:</p>

    <h3>Branch approach (not recommended)</h3>

    <pre data-lang="bash"><code># dev branch    -> deploys to dev
# staging branch -> deploys to staging
# main branch   -> deploys to production

# Problem: promotions are done via merge/cherry-pick
# between branches. It's fragile and error-prone.
# Branches diverge easily.</code></pre>

    <h3>Folder approach (recommended)</h3>

    <pre data-lang="bash"><code># A single branch (main), folders per environment
# overlays/dev/       -> deploys to dev
# overlays/staging/   -> deploys to staging
# overlays/production/ -> deploys to production

# Promotion: modify the image tag in the next folder
# 1. Test in dev  : modify overlays/dev/kustomization.yaml
# 2. Promote      : copy the same tag to overlays/staging/
# 3. Ship to prod : copy the tag to overlays/production/

# Advantage: a single git log shows the full history
# of all environments. No branch divergence.</code></pre>

    <div class="tip">
      <p><strong>Tip:</strong> The GitOps community strongly recommends the folder approach. Branches per environment seem intuitive at first, but quickly become a maintenance nightmare when environments diverge.</p>
    </div>

